:::summary
Western philosophy is the intellectual tradition stretching from the ancient Greeks through Rome, the Christian Middle Ages, the Renaissance, the Enlightenment, and into the modern era — a continuous conversation across twenty-five centuries about the nature of reality, knowledge, morality, and the good society. It is the tradition that gave the world formal logic, natural law, science, democracy, and the university, and it has been shaped at every stage by the creative tension between Greek reason and Christian faith. Understanding Western philosophy is essential to understanding Western civilization — and to understanding oneself as an heir of the greatest intellectual tradition in human history.
